<sect>Installation
<p>
<sect1>How to obtain KMedia
<p>
KMedia is a core application of the KDE project <url url="http://www.kde.org">.
KMedia can be found on <url url="ftp://ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/">, the main ftp site
of the KDE project.

<sect1>Requirements
<p>
In order to successfully compile KMedia, you need the latest versions of <tt> libkdecore</tt>
and <tt> libkdeui</tt>. All required libraries as well as KMedia itself can be found
on <url url="ftp://ftp.kde.org/pub/kde/">. 



<sect1>Compilation and installation
<p>

In order to compile and install KMedia on your system, type the following in the base 
directory of the KMedia distribution:
<tscreen><verb>
% ./configure
% make
% make install
</verb></tscreen>


Since KMedia uses <tt>autoconf</tt> you should have not trouble compiling it.
Should you run into problems please report them to the <sf/KDE/ mailing lists.

<sect>Onscreen Fundamentals
<p>

KMedia usage is simple. Start the program and drag a WAV file into the
window. The file will be played immediately. If the file does not get played
your sound device might be busy.


<p>

<sect1>Buttons
<p>
The meaning of all buttons should be well known. If you can operate a tape deck or
CD Player, you should have no problem in using KMedia. Only applicable buttons
are usable. For example, ejecting a CD makes sense, but not ejecting a WAV Media.



<sect1>Multiple media players
<p>
You can open multiple KMedia windows. Either by using File->New view
or by starting another media player through kpanel.

If you want KMedia to use a specific output device (e.g. soundcard)
you can set it in kmedia's configuration dialog. Attention: This is
currently unimplemented!!!
You can set  the device using numbers. 0 means the default
device, 1 the primary, 2 the secondary device and so on.






<p>
<sect1> Key Bindings
<p>
KMedia honors the following key binding.


<itemize>
<item><tt/Control-N/ Open new media player window
</itemize>

